Osteoblasts (Ob) are cuboid to columnar cells located on the surface of existing bone matrix (B), and onto which they secrete osteoid (Os); note in the micrograph on the right that the newly-secreted osteoid does not stain as intensely as the established, mineralized matrix onto which it is secreted. Osteoblasts subsequently mineralize the osteoid they produce.
Osteoblasts may 1) become quiescent as bone-lining cells (periosteal or endosteal â€“ these squamous cells resemble osteoprogenitor cells); 2) die by apoptosis; or 3) become surrounded by the matrix they produce and differentiate further into osteocytes.
Two osteoblasts depicted in figure (A) are becoming surrounded by the osteoid they produced and are in the process of becoming osteocytes; these two cells are marked with an asterisk *. Osteoblasts extend fine cell processes into the osteoid they produce and maintain contact with adjacent bone cells (osteoblasts and osteocytes) via both adherent and gap junctions. As the osteoid around these cell processes becomes mineralized, it creates canaliculi, microscopic channels in the bone matrix containing the cell processes as well as a very small, but critically important volume of tissue fluid.
